Very quick trip to #SLC for (my 10th time at!) the #RootsTech conference, where we all gather to nerd out about genealogical technology. Last time here was February of 2020, and on the 3rd day I checked into urgent care with a mysterious 104 degree fever. Whether or not that was early COVID I guess we'll never know, but it's sure nice to be back in these amazing mountains.

I'm honored to be nominated for a @csacasting Artios Award for the 2022 off-Broadway production of @americanothemusical - it was a privilege to put together that cast of 25 wonderful performers. I'm unable to attend the in-person ceremony tonight due to a scheduling conflict, but I want to wish all of my colleagues and fellow nominees the very best as we celebrate the casting profession, and fight for its continued recognition. #Artios38 #CSACasting

I just heard that Max Morath has passed away at the age of 96. He's here (in the bow tie), along with me (at the age of 23!), and two incredibly important people in my life: Peter Howard (who I worked for during my first years in NY), and my great friend Judd Woldin (whose score for RAISIN is one of the reasons I work in the theatre). 3 of the greatest pianists who ever graced the planet, and I somehow snuck my mug into the shot.

Saw it twice pre-Broadway, in Chicago at the Goodman, then caught the first preview and maybe a dozen subsequent performances on Broadway, saw the first national, and maybe a half-dozen regional productions since. And now: Encores!

My 21st birthday was spent mostly in a car, with two notable destinations. I got up early and drove from Westerville, Ohio (where I was in my junior year as a musical theatre major at Otterbein), and my first destination was Ann Arbor, Michigan - where I got to see Stanley Bahorek and Meghan Randolph be brilliant in a production of PARADE at U of M. I didn't stay long, though, because in Findlay, Ohio (90 minutes from there and vaguely on my way back to Columbus) there was (somewhat inexplicably!) going to be a concert of cut songs from REX, a passion project of Professor Mike Anders -- and Sheldon Harnick himself was going to be there. 

Can you think of a better way to spend one's 21st birthday?!?

I've just heard the news that Sheldon is no longer with us, but in so many incredibly real ways, he'll always be here. His lyrics changed the game, bringing so much humanity/craft/beauty/heart into the world. Hos work has impacted just about every day of my life since I was a teenager and, though we never knew each other particularly well in life, I (like all of us) could tell *exactly* what he looked like, inside. Our interactions in the years that followed were among the very few moments I've considered myself fully starstruck. 

Here's a picture from my 21st birthday, when I got to meet one of my heroes.
